<subSubSection id="E9B0A7A47F31FFE0FF3F720EFE9CFA04" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A115F42F7F31FFE0FF3F720EFBE1FE74" blockId="4.[151,1437,297,1502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
The original description of 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FE79720DFDA4FE99" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[465,622,298,323]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FE79720DFDA4FE99" box="[465,622,298,323]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(and until 1853) only included few aspects of the male coloration (Fabricius 1789). 
<bibRefCitation id="C53B89DE7F31FFE0FE95726AFDAAFEBD" author="Selys-Longchamps, E. de" box="[317,608,332,359]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" pagination="1 - 404" refId="ref6326" refString="Selys-Longchamps, E. de (1853) Synopsis des Calopterygines. Bulletins de L'Academie Royale Des Sciencies Des Lettres Et Des Beaux-Arts De Belgique, 1853, 1 - 404." type="journal article" year="1853">Selys-Longchamps (1853</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="C53B89DE7F31FFE0FDC6726BFD6DFEBD" author="Selys-Longchamps, E. de" box="[622,679,332,359]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" pagination="1 - 878" refId="ref6358" refString="Selys-Longchamps, E. de (1854) Monographie des Calopterygines. Memoires de la Societe Royal des Sciences de Liege, 1854, 1 - 878. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 60461" type="journal article" year="1854">1854</bibRefCitation>
) made a more precise description of the species including a small description of the females. The first illustration of the cerci of 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FCCD7255FBCBFE51" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[869,1025,370,395]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FCCD7255FBCBFE51" box="[869,1025,370,395]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was included in 
<bibRefCitation id="C53B89DE7F31FFE0FB6E7256FF11FE75" author="Selys-Longchamps, E. de" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" pagination="1 - 878" refId="ref6358" refString="Selys-Longchamps, E. de (1854) Monographie des Calopterygines. Memoires de la Societe Royal des Sciences de Liege, 1854, 1 - 878. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 60461" type="journal article" year="1854">Selys-Longchamps (1854</bibRefCitation>
; Plate 12, 
<figureCitation id="3991E8AA7F31FFE0FEF872B3FE59FE75" box="[336,403,404,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[190,1389,191,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[184,1403,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Variation between H. calverti and H. americana males. Male cerci (dorsal and mediodorsal view) of H. calverti (A) and H. americana (B). The illustrations are not at scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765637" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765637/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
, pp. 331). The author described the appendages as follows:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A115F42F7F31FFE0FF6F729FFC9DFDBB" blockId="4.[151,1437,297,1502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
“ 
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FF7C729FFC9DFDBB" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">Anal appendages yellow, black at their extremities; the superiors cylindrical, arched, little toothed on the outside; the superior ridge ends in a semicircle before the tip, which is a little thicker, cylindrical, obtuse, a little depressed on the inner lower edge that offers, from the middle to a little before the tip, a very strong dilatation flattened, which is preceded by an excavation below. This dentate dilation in the middle, in profile view, is a fairly large obtuse medial tooth, ending in a very small and rounded tooth.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A115F42F7F31FFE0FF6F714CFD97FD73" blockId="4.[151,1437,297,1502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FF6F714CFD83FD73" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">Inferior appendages are shorter than half of the superior ones, straight, cylindrical, obtuse, separated; its internal angle is weak, with a hair brush</emphasis>
”.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A115F42F7F31FFE0FF6F7195FE9DFCA5" blockId="4.[151,1437,297,1502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
After these descriptions, Hagen 
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FD827194FD8AFD16" box="[554,576,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C53B89DE7F31FFE0FDEE7195FCA6FD17" author="Selys-Longchamps, E. de" box="[582,876,690,717]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" pagination="1 - 696" refId="ref6400" refString="Selys-Longchamps, E. de (1859) Additiones au synopsis des Calopterygines. Bulletins de L'Academie Royale Des Sciencies Des Lettres Et Des Beaux-Arts De Belgique, 2, 1 - 696." type="journal article" year="1859">Selys-Longchamps (1859)</bibRefCitation>
delved into the variation existing within 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FA997194FF07FD2A" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FA997194FF07FD2A" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and suggested two new species: 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FD9171F0FD1FFD2A" authorityName="Hagen in Selys-Longchamps" authorityYear="1859" box="[569,725,726,752]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californica">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FD9171F0FD1FFD2A" box="[569,725,726,752]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. californica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FCA171F0FCB0FD2A" baseAuthorityName="Selys-Longchamps" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[777,890,726,752]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FCA171F0FCB0FD2A" box="[777,890,726,752]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The first species differs in the shape of the cerci, which is quadrangular, and also in that the pterostigma is absent. This species is restricted to Northern 
<collectingRegion id="636E3ACD7F31FFE0FA8C71DDFA53FCCE" box="[1316,1433,762,788]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">California</collectingRegion>
. The second species, 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FE287039FE38FCE2" baseAuthorityName="Selys-Longchamps" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[384,498,798,824]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FE287039FE38FCE2" box="[384,498,798,824]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. basalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is characterized by having a much larger red wing spot than Hagen’s definition of 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FF3F7065FEFBFC81" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[151,305,834,859]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FF3F7065FEFBFC81" box="[151,305,834,859]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(i.e. reaching the node) and a triangular median lobe in the cerci. Hagen suggested that this is a ‘race’ of 
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FF1E7041FE9DFCA5" box="[182,343,870,895]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FF1E7041FE99FCA5" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[182,339,870,895]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">H. americana</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A115F42F7F31FFE0FF6F70AEFB4DFBD4" blockId="4.[151,1437,297,1502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
<bibRefCitation id="C53B89DE7F31FFE0FF6F70AEFE95FC7E" author="Walsh, B. D." box="[199,351,905,932]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" pagination="1 - 602" refId="ref6563" refString="Walsh, B. D. (1863) Observations on certain N. A. Neuroptera. Proceedings of Entomological Society of Philadelphia, 2, 1 - 602." type="journal article" year="1863">Walsh (1863)</bibRefCitation>
suggested three new species from the review of several specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FBD570ADFAD2FC79" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[1149,1304,906,931]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FBD570ADFAD2FC79" box="[1149,1304,906,931]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FA8F70ADFEEAFC1D" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FA8F70ADFA52FC79" authorityName="Walsh" authorityYear="1863" box="[1319,1432,906,931]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="texana">H. texana</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FF3F708AFEEAFC1D" baseAuthorityName="Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="1863" box="[151,288,941,967]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scelerata">H. scelerata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FEFC708AFDF6FC1D" box="[340,572,941,967]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudoamericana">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FEFC708AFDF6FC1D" box="[340,572,941,967]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. pseudoamericana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In general, these species differ, according to Walsh, in small variations of the cerci as well as in the extension and coloration of the red spot and in the presence and coloration of the pterostigma. It should be noted that all the individuals reviewed by Walsh were from 
<collectingCountry id="D9BDB4BF7F31FFE0FC1770D3FC3FFBD4" box="[959,1013,1012,1038]" name="United States of America" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">USA</collectingCountry>
populations.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A115F42F7F31FFE0FF6F773FFE7AFB3E" blockId="4.[151,1437,297,1502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
Finally, 
<bibRefCitation id="C53B89DE7F31FFE0FE8C773FFE00FBE8" author="Calvert, P. P." box="[292,458,1048,1074]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" pagination="1 - 470" refId="ref5670" refString="Calvert, P. P. (1901) Odonata. In: Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, O. (Eds.), Biologia Centrali-Americana: Isecta Neuroptera Biologia Centrali Americana: Insecta Neuroptera. R. H. Porter &amp; Dulau Co., London, pp. 1 - 470. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 730" type="book chapter" year="1901">Calvert (1901)</bibRefCitation>
included the first specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="D9BDB4BF7F31FFE0FCF2773FFC7AFBE8" box="[858,944,1048,1074]" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="D9BDB4BF7F31FFE0FC41773FFBAFFBE8" box="[1001,1125,1048,1074]" name="Guatemala" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
, and in his Plate II, figures 6, 11 and 15, drew the appendages of what we suggest is the here described new species. Calvert commented that, in a population from Tamaulipas he examined individuals that showed cerci of this shape, as well as others such as those shown in figure 16 that correspond to 
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FD2B77A3FC7AFB47" box="[643,944,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FD2B77A3FCD7FB47" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[643,797,1156,1181]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">H. americana</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="88ED95467F31FFE0FC8B77A3FC7AFB47" box="[803,944,1156,1181]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" sensu="stricto">sensu stricto</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(i.e. they were in sympatry). The difference between individuals was only recognized by this character, since the coloration and extension of the red spot in the two 
<typeStatus id="7E114A8D7F31FFE0FF6077ECFEC9FB3F" box="[200,259,1227,1253]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">types</typeStatus>
were identical.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A115F42F7F31FFE0FF6F77C9FCAEFA8A" blockId="4.[151,1437,297,1502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
Calvert suggested that the variation in the shape of the cerci was not correlated with the geographical location or the season in which the individuals were collected. Finally, Calvert suggested that all the aforementioned species belong to a single 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FECC7611FE35FA95" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[356,511,1334,1359]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FECC7611FE35FA95" box="[356,511,1334,1359]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, which is very variable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A115F42F7F31FFE0FF6F767DFE9CFA04" blockId="4.[151,1437,297,1502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
From this review, we found no evidence that any of the synonyms that were described for 
<taxonomicName id="66AA8FAC7F31FFE0FB1F767DFA9BFAA9" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[1207,1361,1370,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Calopterygidae" genus="Hetaerina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FB1F767DFA9BFAA9" box="[1207,1361,1370,1395]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">H. americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
match the new species suggested by 
<bibRefCitation id="C53B89DE7F31FFE0FE4F765AFCD0FA4D" author="Vega-Sanchez, Y. M. &amp; Mendoza-Cuenca, L. F. &amp; Gonzalez-Rodriguez, A." box="[487,794,1405,1431]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" pagination="1 - 11" refId="ref6497" refString="Vega-Sanchez, Y. M., Mendoza-Cuenca, L. F. &amp; Gonzalez-Rodriguez, A. (2019) Complex evolutionary history of the American Rubyspot damselfly, Hetaerina americana (Odonata): Evidence of cryptic speciation. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 139, 1 - 11. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2019.106536" type="journal article" year="2019">
Vega-Sánchez 
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FD257659FD0CFA4D" box="[653,710,1405,1431]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
. The only report that included illustrations of the cerci of this new species is the work of 
<bibRefCitation id="C53B89DE7F31FFE0FE467686FD59FA61" author="Calvert, P. P." box="[494,659,1441,1467]" pageId="4" pageNumber="489" pagination="1 - 470" refId="ref5670" refString="Calvert, P. P. (1901) Odonata. In: Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, O. (Eds.), Biologia Centrali-Americana: Isecta Neuroptera Biologia Centrali Americana: Insecta Neuroptera. R. H. Porter &amp; Dulau Co., London, pp. 1 - 470. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 730" type="book chapter" year="1901">Calvert (1901)</bibRefCitation>
, nevertheless it is in this paper that the author synonymized all species in 
<emphasis id="93DE283D7F31FFE0FF1C76E2FE9CFA04" box="[180,342,1477,1502]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="489">
